            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text is a continuation of *Walking Among the letters*. Therefore, we recommend reading it before proceeding",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7510e065-7fba-42a5-baed-c67061158b01",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Walking among letters",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nLetters of the alphabet group together to form syllables. A better understanding of this process helps us differentiate and comprehend words more clearly.\n\nIn this text, we will explore the structure of words in greater depth. At the end, we will present a game to reinforce this knowledge.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_phoneme",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Phonemes\n\nIn our previous text, we explored vowels and some interjections. However, vowels are not the only representations of sounds in our language. In addition to vowels, we also have consonants, which are defined as",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "c2344ae1-c487-40a4-b1d1-35f3fa99cda8",
                     "text": "Cambridge Dictionary, consonant",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"one of the speech sounds or letters of the alphabet that is not a vowel. Consonants are pronounced by stopping the air from flowing easily through the mouth, especially by closing the lips or touching the teeth with the tongue.\"</i></li> </ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "This definition highlights a key aspect when compared to the definition of vowels",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "45e4fa81-8a80-4197-a19b-7ba9ac719097",
                     "text": "Cambridge Dictionary, vowel",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"a speech sound produced by humans when the breath flows out through the mouth without being blocked by the teeth, tongue, or lips.\"</i></li> </ul></p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1:  A Common Point</b><br /><br />When observing both definitions, can you identify something they have in common?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Both definitions relate to the sounds we produce when pronouncing a letter. Because of this, both vowels and consonants are defined as **phonemes**",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "fae46f03-9e81-4a75-afc0-fde1a45290e3",
                     "text": "Cambridge Dictionary, phoneme",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_alphabet",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Alphabet\n\n#### Organization\n\nThe sounds produced by consonants and vowels are organized in a sequence called the alphabet",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "eb0be542-c4be-431e-8e0a-342502118d2b",
                     "text": "Cambridge Dictionary, alphabet",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul></li><li>a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, i, j, k, l, m, n, o, p, q, r, s, t, u, v, w, x, y, z</li></ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In the alphabet, consonants and vowels are placed together without explicit separation. Since we have definitions for each of them, we can group them into different categories based on their characteristics:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul></li><li><b>Consonants:</b> {b, c, d, f, g, h, j, k, l, m, n, p, q, r, s, t, v, x, z}</li><li><b>Vowels:</b> {a, e, i, o, u}</ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "We highlight that, in the classification presented, the letters *w* and *y* were not included, as their categorization depends on the context in which they are used within a word.\n\n#### Origin\n\nAlthough it is natural for us to represent the alphabet in its current form, this was not always the case. According to one theory, when the Egyptians first developed the alphabet, it consisted of 22 hieroglyphs representing syllables with consonant and vowel sounds (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nOver time, other cultures developed their own alphabets. Chronologically, the Phoenicians are notable for creating a writing system that represented consonant sounds but lacked symbols for vowels (<htcite3>; <htcite4>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "714a08f1-5ace-4d75-90c6-7b78e6146e9b",
                     "text": "Crabben, J.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2011",
                        "month": "04",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f2865e84-bedf-4ad0-8059-c2e97f875946",
                     "text": "Olson, D. R. and Diringer, D.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "04a47abe-5803-4db3-b2e8-2ce869c86fd9",
                     "text": "Herraiz, Elena",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "714a08f1-5ace-4d75-90c6-7b78e6146e9b",
                     "text": "Crabben, J.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2011",
                        "month": "04",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f2865e84-bedf-4ad0-8059-c2e97f875946",
                     "text": "Olson, D. R. and Diringer, D.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
